       = studio\n| artist     = [[Machine Gun Kelly (rapper)|Machine Gun Kelly]]\n| cover      = MGKLaceUp.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2012|10|9}}\n| recorded   = 2010&ndash;12\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=63|s=59}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Sean Combs|Diddy]] <small>([[Executive producer#Music|exec]].)</small>|[[Machine Gun Kelly (rapper)|MGK]] <small>(also exec.)</small>|[[Harve Pierre]] <small>(co-exec.)</small>|James McMillan <small>(co-exec.)</small>|[[Alex da Kid]]|Alex Kickdrum|Aliby|Anna Yvette|[[Boi-1da]]|[[Dame Grease]]|Snaz|Jazzfeezy|[[Drumma Boy]]|[[Frequency (record producer)|Frequency]]|GB Hitz|[[J.R. Rotem]]|[[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]]|[[JP Did This 1]]|JRB|Rami Beatz|Silent Mike|Slim Gudz|[[Southside (record producer)|Southside]]|Swirv|Syk Sense|Woodro Skillson}}\n| prev_title = [[Half Naked & Almost Famous]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[Black Flag (mixtape)|Black Flag]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Lace Up\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Wild Boy (song)|Wild Boy]]\n | single1date = September 27, 2011\n | single2     = [[Invincible (MGK song)|Invincible]]\n | single2date = April 24, 2012\n | single3     = [[Hold On (Shut Up)]]\n | single3date = August 6, 2012\n }}\n}}\n\n'''''Lace Up''''' is the debut studio album by American rapper [[Machine Gun Kelly (rapper)|Machine Gun Kelly]]. It was released on October 9, 2012, by [[Bad Boy Records]] and [[Interscope Records]].<ref name=\"releasedate\">{{cite web|last=Harling|first=Danielle|title=Machine Gun Kelly \"Lace Up\" Release Date|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.20584/title.machine-gun-kelly-lace-up-release-date|magazine=[[HipHopDX]]|publisher=Cheri Media Group|accessdate=August 31, 2012|date=August 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104052546/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.20584/title.machine-gun-kelly-lace-up-release-date|archive-date=November 4, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Sean Combs|Puff Daddy]], who served as the executive producer on the album, enlisted the guest appearances from [[Cassie Ventura|Cassie]], [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]], [[Planet VI]] and [[Avenged Sevenfold]];<ref name=\"releasedate\"/> as well as the production that was provided by [[Alex da Kid]], [[JP Did This 1]] and [[J.R. Rotem]], among others. The album was supported by four singles: \"[[Wild Boy (song)|Wild Boy]]\" featuring [[Waka Flocka Flame]], \"[[Invincible (MGK song)|Invincible]]\" featuring [[Ester Dean]], and \"[[Hold On (Shut Up)]]\" featuring [[Young Jeezy]], along with a promotional single, \"[[Stereo (MGK song)|Stereo]]\" featuring Alex Fitts.\n\nReviews for the record were generally positive, but critics felt that it was a disappointment, compared to his previous mixtapes. ''Lace Up'' debuted at number 4 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 57,000 copies in the United States. It was certified Gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting sales of over 500,000 copies.\n\n== Singles ==\nThe album's lead single, \"[[Wild Boy (song)|Wild Boy]]\" was released on September 27, 2011. The song features guest vocals from fellow American rapper [[Waka Flocka Flame]], with production being provided by GB Hitz and [[Southside (producer)|Southside]]. It was initially featured on his fourth mixtape, ''Rage Pack'' (2011), and on his debut [[Extended play|EP]], ''[[Half Naked & Almost Famous]]'' (2012). The song debuted at number 98 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on the week of January 28, 2012, and number 49 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart. It serves as his first song to be charted on both ''Billboard'' charts.<ref>{{cite journal|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=mgk|chart=Hot 100}}|title=MGK Album & Song Chart History \u2013 The Billboard Hot 100|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=September 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=mgk|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Songs}}|title=MGK Album & Song Chart History \u2013 Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|journal=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=September 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe album's second single, \"[[Invincible (MGK song)|Invincible]]\" was released to digital retailers in the United States on April 24, 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Invincible (feat. Ester Dean) \u2013 Single by MGK|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/invincible-feat.-ester-dean/id518868522|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (US). [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]|accessdate=August 31, 2012}}</ref> and was solicited to rhythmic contemporary radio and contemporary hit radio on May 15 to July 31, 2012, respectively.<ref name=\"FMQB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239#2012 |title=FMQB: Radio Industry News, Music Industry Updates, Arbitron Ratings, Music News and more! |work=[[FMQB]] |publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report, Inc |accessdate=August 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QujmdbEt?url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239 |archivedate=July 8, 2014 }}</ref> The song features guest vocals from American singer-songwriter [[Ester Dean]], and was produced by British producer [[Alex da Kid]]. MGK shot a music video for the single, which features an appearance from the singer Ester Dean, and uploaded the video on [[YouTube]] under his [[Vevo|VEVO]] account, on June 3, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Video: MGK f/ Ester Dean - 'Invincible{{'-}}|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/06/03/video-mgk-f-ester-dean-invincible/|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devin Lazerine|accessdate=August 31, 2012|date=June 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Hold On (Shut Up)]]\" featuring [[Young Jeezy]], was released as the album's third single on August 6, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/music-video/hold-on-shut-up/id579822815|title=iTunes - Music Videos - Hold On (Shut Up) by MGK|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple|accessdate=December 22, 2013}}</ref> The music video was released on November 19, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstarhiphop.com/videos/video.php?v=wshhqTUlTgs9tN15YnlV |title=Video: Machine Gun Kelly (Feat. Young Jeezy) - Hold On (Shut Up) |publisher=WorldStarHipHop |date=December 4, 2012 |accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Promotional singles ===\nOn September 20, 2012, \"[[Stereo (MGK Song)|Stereo]]\" was released with an accompanying music video, as the album's promotional single (although this track was formerly part of the mixtape with same title as the album). The song features guest vocals from Alex Fitts. The track would also be included, alongside \"Invincible\" and \"Hold On (Shut Up)\", as part of the MGK's Music Unlimited exclusive EP, titled ''Lace Up - The Prelude'' (released on October 2, 2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.sonyentertainmentnetwork.com/album/16c66e36377d4405aa15c2340180224e/MGK/Lace_Up_The_Prelude_ |title=MGK / Lace Up (The Prelude) |work=[[Music Unlimited]] |publisher=[[Sony Entertainment Network]] |accessdate=October 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221220302/https://music.sonyentertainmentnetwork.com/album/16c66e36377d4405aa15c2340180224e/MGK/Lace_Up_The_Prelude_ |archivedate=December 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 69/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|title=Reviews for Lace Up by MGK|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/lace-up/mgk|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=lace-up-mw0002419661/|pure_url=yes}}|title=Lace Up - Machine Gun Kelly|last=Thomas|first=Fred|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=October 18, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = DJBooth\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"DJBooth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/machine-gun-kelly-lace-up|title=Machine Gun Kelly - Lace Up|last=Slavik|first=Nathan|website=DJBooth|date=October 9, 2012|accessdate=January 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203035623/http://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/machine-gun-kelly-lace-up|archive-date=February 3, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"HHDX\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hiphopdx.com/index/album-reviews/id.1977/title.machine-gun-kelly-lace-up|title=Machine Gun Kelly - Lace Up|last=Ortiz|first=Edwin|magazine=HipHopDX|publisher=Cheri Media Group|date=October 25, 2012|accessdate=September 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028064946/https://www.hiphopdx.com/index/album-reviews/id.1977/title.machine-gun-kelly-lace-up|archive-date=October 28, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/lace-up-20121109|title=MGK Lace Up Album Review|last=Dolan|first=Jon|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=November 9, 2012|accessdate=January 3, 2013}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev5Score = 5/10<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/mgk-lace-up-bad-boyinterscope/|title=MGK, 'Lace Up' Review|last=Mlynar|first=Phillip|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|date=October 17, 2012|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''\n| rev6Score = 4/5 (XL)<ref name=\"XXL\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/reviews/2012/10/machine-gun-kelly-lace-up/|title=Machine Gun Kelly, Lace Up|last=Fleischer|first=Adam|magazine=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|date=October 11, 2012|accessdate=January 3, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n''Lace Up'' received favorable reviews but music critics found the record overall uneven, compared to Kelly's previous mixtapes. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received average score of 69, based on 6 reviews which indicates generally favourable reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> Adam Fleischer of ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' praised the production throughout the album and MGK for being consistent with his rapid-fire flow concluding with, \"though he may no longer be quite the underdog he once was, rapping like it\u2014at least for now\u2014still works.\"<ref name=\"XXL\"/> Fred Thomas of [[AllMusic]] also praised the album for its production and putting MGK in the spotlight, calling it \"a beast of a debut, and some of the heaviest mainstream-friendly hip-hop happening in 2012, a picture of young energy at its zenith.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n\nEdwin Ortiz of ''[[HipHopDX]]'' gave a mixed review of the album, praising tracks like \"Edge of Destruction\" and \"D3mons\" for their intensity but found \"Invincible\" and \"All We Have\" put MGK into \"industry purgatory.\" He concluded with, \"''Lace Up'' is an imbalanced project that fails to establish MGK\u2019s grand message. His debut is decent at best, with hope that his following projects yield better results.\"<ref name=\"HHDX\"/> Phillip Mlynar of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' felt that the special guests throughout the album were more of a hindrance to the main artist saying, \"Instead of turning this debut proper into an expansive listen, the guests seem like they're papering over holes in both the music and the message.\"<ref name=\"Spin\"/>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nThe album debuted at number 4 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 57,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474608/macklemore-ryan-lewis-score-top-billboard-200-debut-mumford-still-no-1|title=Macklemore & Ryan Lewis Score Top Billboard 200 Debut, Mumford Still No. 1|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=October 17, 2012|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref> It slid down to number 22 in its second week giving it a total of 65,000 copies.<ref name=\"HipHopDX\">{{cite web|last=Jacobs|first=Allen|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 10/21/2012|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.21629/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-10-21-2012|work=HipHopDX|publisher=Cheri Media Group|date=October 21, 2012|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121123083940/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.21629/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-10-21-2012|archive-date=November 23, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sliding down to number 37 in week three it sold 10,000 more copies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Paine|first=Jake|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 10/28/2012|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.21709/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-10-28-2012|work=HipHopDX|publisher=Cheri Media Group|date=October 28, 2012|accessdate=October 31, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104001920/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.21709/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-10-28-2012|archive-date=November 4, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> As of September 2015, the album has sold 263,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150917090733/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= September 17, 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |website=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nAlbum credits adapted from official liner notes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.docdroid.net/dI0Ye5p/digital-booklet-lace-up.pdf.html|title=Digital Booklet - Lace Up |publisher=DocDroid|accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = ''Lace Up'' {{nobold|&nbsp;\u2014 