{"title_page": "Comporium Communications", "text_new": "{{Infobox company |\n  name   = Comporium is Garbage |\n  logo   = |\n  type   = [[Private company]]  |\n  founded        = 1894 |\n  location       = [[Rock Hill, South Carolina|Rock Hill]], [[South Carolina|SC]], [[United States|U.S.]]|                \n  key_people     = Bryant G. Barnes - [[President (corporate title)|President]] & [[CEO]]|                     \n  num_employees  = 1,000+|\n  industry       = [[Telecommunications]]| has \n  products       = Landline Telephone Service, High-Speed Internet, Wireless Internet, Digital TV, Wireless Telephone (AT&T), and Security|\n  homepage       = [http://www.comporium.com Comporium Homepage]|\n  revenue        = |\n}}\n\n'''Comporium Communications''' is a local [[telephone]], [[internet]], [[Cable television|cable]] and home security provider that centrally operates in [[York County, South Carolina|York]] and [[Lancaster County, South Carolina|Lancaster]] counties in the north-central section of [[South Carolina]].  The Corporate headquarters of Comporium is located at the intersection of Black Street and Elizabeth Lane in the city of [[Rock Hill, South Carolina|Rock Hill]], [[South Carolina]], [[United States]].  There are also local cable channels owned and operated by Comporium such as, Cable News 2 (CN2), CN2 eXtra, and [[The Weather Channel]]'s local [[Weatherscan]] for Rock Hill.<ref>[http://www.comporium.com/ Comporium - Homepage]</ref>\n\n==Locations==\nComporium Communications offers services in parts or all of the following counties:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.comporium.com/29734/find-a-retail-location/ |title=Comporium - Locations |access-date=2011-11-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401150602/http://www.comporium.com/29734/find-a-retail-location/ |archive-date=2012-04-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== South Carolina ===\n*[[Aiken County, South Carolina|Aiken]]\n*[[Calhoun County, South Carolina|Calhoun]]\n*[[Chester County, South Carolina|Chester]]\n*[[Edgefield County, South Carolina|Edgefield]]\n*[[Lancaster County, South Carolina|Lancaster]]\n*[[Lexington County, South Carolina|Lexington]]\n*[[Orangeburg County, South Carolina|Orangeburg]]\n*[[Saluda County, South Carolina|Saluda]]\n*[[York County, South Carolina|York]]\n\n=== North Carolina ===\n*[[Mecklenburg County, North Carolina|Mecklenburg]] \u2014 Serving the Ayrsley area in [[Steele Creek (Charlotte neighborhood)|Steele Creek]] and areas of [[Pineville, North Carolina|Pineville]].\n*[[Transylvania County, North Carolina|Transylvania]]\n\n==History==\nIn 1894, John Anderson, John Cherry and Andrew Smith founded the Rock Hill Telephone Company.  E. L. and Mary Barnes bought the company in 1912; their great-grandchildren still run the company today.  \nIn 2001, Rock Hill Telephone Company and its affiliates became known as \"Comporium,\" a word created from \"Communications\" and \"Emporium\"\u2014 a one-stop shop for a variety of products and services.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.comporium.com/29734/about-about-comporium-who-we-are/ |title=Comporium - About |access-date=2011-11-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401150612/http://www.comporium.com/29734/about-about-comporium-who-we-are/ |archive-date=2012-04-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cable television companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Rock Hill, South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company |\n  name   = Comporium Communications |\n  logo   = |\n  type   = [[Private company]]  |\n  founded        = 1894 |\n  location       = [[Rock Hill, South Carolina|Rock Hill]], [[South Carolina|SC]], [[United States|U.S.]]|                \n  key_people     = Bryant G. Barnes - [[President (corporate title)|President]] & [[CEO]]|                     \n  num_employees  = 1,000+|\n  industry       = [[Telecommunications]]| \n  products       = Landline Telephone Service, High-Speed Internet, Wireless Internet, Digital TV, Wireless Telephone (AT&T), and Security|\n  homepage       = [http://www.comporium.com Comporium Homepage]|\n  revenue        = |\n}}\n\n'''Comporium Communications''' is a local [[telephone]], [[internet]], [[Cable television|cable]] and home security provider that centrally operates in [[York County, South Carolina|York]] and [[Lancaster County, South Carolina|Lancaster]] counties in the north-central section of [[South Carolina]].  The Corporate headquarters of Comporium is located at the intersection of Black Street and Elizabeth Lane in the city of [[Rock Hill, South Carolina|Rock Hill]], [[South Carolina]], [[United States]].  There are also local cable channels owned and operated by Comporium such as, Cable News 2 (CN2), CN2 eXtra, and [[The Weather Channel]]'s local [[Weatherscan]] for Rock Hill.<ref>[http://www.comporium.com/ Comporium - Homepage]</ref>\n\n==Locations==\nComporium Communications offers services in parts or all of the following counties:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.comporium.com/29734/find-a-retail-location/ |title=Comporium - Locations |access-date=2011-11-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401150602/http://www.comporium.com/29734/find-a-retail-location/ |archive-date=2012-04-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== South Carolina ===\n*[[Aiken County, South Carolina|Aiken]]\n*[[Calhoun County, South Carolina|Calhoun]]\n*[[Chester County, South Carolina|Chester]]\n*[[Edgefield County, South Carolina|Edgefield]]\n*[[Lancaster County, South Carolina|Lancaster]]\n*[[Lexington County, South Carolina|Lexington]]\n*[[Orangeburg County, South Carolina|Orangeburg]]\n*[[Saluda County, South Carolina|Saluda]]\n*[[York County, South Carolina|York]]\n\n=== North Carolina ===\n*[[Mecklenburg County, North Carolina|Mecklenburg]] \u2014 Serving the Ayrsley area in [[Steele Creek (Charlotte neighborhood)|Steele Creek]] and areas of [[Pineville, North Carolina|Pineville]].\n*[[Transylvania County, North Carolina|Transylvania]]\n\n==History==\nIn 1894, John Anderson, John Cherry and Andrew Smith founded the Rock Hill Telephone Company.  E. L. and Mary Barnes bought the company in 1912; their great-grandchildren still run the company today.  \nIn 2001, Rock Hill Telephone Company and its affiliates became known as \"Comporium,\" a word created from \"Communications\" and \"Emporium\"\u2014 a one-stop shop for a variety of products and services.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.comporium.com/29734/about-about-comporium-who-we-are/ |title=Comporium - About |access-date=2011-11-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401150612/http://www.comporium.com/29734/about-about-comporium-who-we-are/ |archive-date=2012-04-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cable television companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Rock Hill, South Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "208.104.70.247", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comporium_Communications"}
{"title_page": "1992 United States presidential election in Wyoming", "text_new": "{{main|1992 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox Election\n| election_name = 1992 [[United States presidential election]] in Wyoming\n| country = Wyoming\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1988 United States presidential election in Wyoming\n| previous_year = 1988\n| next_election = 1996 United States presidential election in Wyoming\n| next_year = 1996\n| election_date = November 3, 1992\n| image_size = x160px\n| image1 = George H. W. Bush presidential portrait (cropped 2).jpg\n| nominee1 = '''[[George H.W. Bush]]''' \n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate1 = '''[[Dan Quayle]]'''\n| electoral_vote1 = '''3'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''79,347'''\n| percentage1 = '''39.70%'''\t\n| image2 = Bill Clinton.jpg\n| nominee2 = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Arkansas]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Al Gore]]\n| electoral_vote2 = 0\n| popular_vote2 = 68,160\n| percentage2 = 34.10%\t\n| image3 = RossPerotColor.jpg\n| nominee3 = [[Ross Perot]]\n| party3 = Independent (politician)\n| home_state3 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate3 = [[James Stockdale]]\n| electoral_vote3 = 0\n| popular_vote3 = 51,263\t\n| percentage3 = 25.65%\n| map_image = WY1992.jpg\n| map_size = 370px\n| map_caption = County Results\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Bush'''\n{{legend|#ffccd0|30\u201340%}}\n{{legend|#f2b3be|40\u201350%}}\n{{legend|#e27f90|50\u201360%}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Clinton'''\n{{legend|#d3e7ff|30\u201340%}}\n{{legend|#b9d7ff|40\u201350%}}\n{{col-end}}\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[George H. W. Bush]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n\n{{ElectionsWY}}\n\nThe '''1992 United States presidential election in Wyoming''' took place on November 3, 1992, as part of the [[1992 United States presidential election]]. Voters chose three representatives, or electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], who voted for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[Wyoming]] was won by incumbent President [[George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Texas]]) with 39.70 percent of the popular vote over Governor [[Bill Clinton]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Arkansas]]) with 34.10 percent. Businessman [[Ross Perot]] ([[Independent politician|I]]-Texas) finished in third, with 25.65 percent of the popular vote.<ref name=results/> Clinton ultimately won the national vote, defeating incumbent President Bush. This election was the closest result Wyoming had had in presidential election history, since [[1948 United States presidential election in Wyoming|1948]], when it narrowly voted for [[Harry S. Truman]] over [[Thomas E. Dewey]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1992|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2016|11|alt=As of the [[2016 United States presidential election in Wyoming|2016 presidential election]]}}, this is the last election in which [[Natrona County, Wyoming|Natrona County]] and [[Carbon County, Wyoming|Carbon County]] voted for the Democratic candidate.<ref name=\"how\">Sullivan, Robert David; [http://www.americamagazine.org/content/unconventional-wisdom/how-red-and-blue-map-evolved-over-past-century \u2018How the Red and Blue Map Evolved Over the Past Century\u2019]; ''America Magazine'' in ''The National Catholic Review''; June 29, 2016</ref> It was also the first time any Wyoming county had voted for a Democrat since [[Jimmy Carter]] won [[Sweetwater County, Wyoming|Sweetwater County]] in [[1976 United States presidential election in Wyoming|1976]], and the first time [[Teton County, Wyoming|Teton County]] voted for a Democratic presidential candidate since it voted for [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] over [[Wendell Willkie]] in [[1940 United States presidential election in Wyoming|1940]].<ref>Menendez, Albert J.; ''The Geography of Presidential Elections in the United States, 1868-2004'', pp. 342-343 {{ISBN|0786422173}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | 1992 United States presidential election in Wyoming<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results \u2013 Wyoming|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1992&off=0&elect=0&fips=56&f=0|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=11 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 17em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Electoral votes\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | '''[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]'''\n| '''[[George H.W. Bush]]''' \n| align=\"right\" | '''79,347'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''39.70%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''3'''\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| [[Bill Clinton]]\n| align=\"right\" | 68,160\n| align=\"right\" | 34.10%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#DDDDCC; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| [[Ross Perot]]\n| align=\"right\" | 51,263\t\n| align=\"right\" | 25.65%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFCC00; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n| [[Andre Marrou]]\n| align=\"right\